previewPlan.name: Suzie's multisport-madness
previewPlan.description:
#### How crazy are you?

For this plan, you must be crazy enough to:

- Swim 5 days/week  
- Cycle 7 days/week  
- Run 6 days/week

_AND Add strength, yoga and MTP_

prospects.name: 2 x (16 x 25m)
prospects.description:
For help understanding your swim workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/SwimSessionFAQ).

​

**Warm Up**

Number of Sets: 1

Number of Repeats: 6 x 100m @ RPE 3-4-- Z2, Focusing on distance per stroke

20 sec rest

​

**Activation**

Number of sets: 1

Number of Repeats: 8

Interval: 50m @ RPE 3-4 -- Z2 as 25 m Side-Glide-Kick drill + 25m swim

- Push off the wall on your side and kick for eight kicks. Keep your ear on your arm and your body straight. Make sure your knees are passing one another when you kick. Eight strokes and then take a good pull with the arm up top. Use this pull to roll you to the other side and repeat the cycle. For variation do this drill with three strokes in between. I.e. on right side with right arm up and left arm at your side. Take a pull with the right, left and right. End with your left arm up and your right arm at your side. This will help improve your body position in the water and if you keep your head on your arm when you are on your side it will help your head position when you breathe. Recovery: 20 sec rest

**Main Set**

Number of Sets: 2

Interval 1: 16 x 25m @ RPE 9 -- Z5

Recovery: 10 sec rest

Interval 2: (Between sets 1 and 2) 100m backstroke or breaststroke @ RPE 2 -- Z1

​

**Cool Down**

200m @ RPE 2 -- Z1, choice of strokes

​

**Total Distance**

1700m

prospects.name: 14 Vise Grips
prospects.description:
You can never have too many tools in the shed. After years of lobbying, we finally convinced Grunter von Agony to share his favorite set of implements with us: the fabled _14 Vise Grips_. Taken individually, each of the 14 intervals might appear tame, incapable of inflicting a significant squeeze. But when expertly applied in the correct order, they apply just the right kind of pressure to turn a Couchlandrian into a Sufferlandrian, just like turning coal into diamonds.

​

While the duration of each Vise Grip varies (from 30 seconds to 2 minutes), the power targets and recovery durations between them remain constant. The first 30-second interval should feel like a Sunday stroll in the park, but by the end of the first 2-minute Vise Grip, you'll be cursing Grunter's name. As the intervals get shorter, time will appear to stretch. That final 30-second effort will feel like an eternity. When you roll up to the second set, you'll know what you're in for, so just put your head down and prepare yourself to crush or be crushed.

​

Once you make it through all 14 Vise Grips, you will have been north of your Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) for a total of 16 minutes. Changing the duration of the efforts (while keeping the same recovery) stresses your Anaerobic Capacity (AC) in a more dynamic way than, say, a more straightforward on/off session like _Half is Easy_. Since the longer efforts have the same recovery duration as the shorter ones, you will eventually deplete your AC, forcing your body to rely on your MAP to hit the required power targets. As the intervals get shorter in the second half of each set, you'll find that you have just enough left in the tank to complete the next effort.

​

Ultimately this workout combines the advantages of shorter, higher-power intervals with longer recovery (great for building muscular strength) with the advantages of longer, higher-power intervals with inadequate recovery (great for driving up your MAP and improving your AC).

prospects.name: A Dog's Life 1
prospects.description:
#### TEST TEXT

Test Text2

Film:

Workout: The workout accompanying this film is a recovery session, which is a very low-intensity ride. It's so easy that your power remains at or below 50% of FTP or an RPE less than 2.5, and your heart rate stays in zone 1 the entire time. The intensity and cadence targets will vary throughout this session to keep it interesting (But not so interesting that you can't pay attention to the film).

prospects.name: AC: 6 x 45s
prospects.description:
There's no getting around the fact that this is a profoundly unpleasant session that will leave your legs feeling like jelly. This session is similar to The Trick, with a few differences. On the plus side, all of the efforts are 15-seconds shorter than those in The Trick. To make up for this, we added two more intervals to this session, bringing the total to 6. That means by the end of this session you will have plowed through 4.5-minutes of AC work.

This workout is one of the few sessions that we do NOT recommend you complete in ERG mode if you are on a smart trainer. The goal is to hold onto the highest power you can for the full 45-seconds. Inevitably in the later sets, your power will dip before you reach the end of the interval. What we want is for you to complete every effort having given everything for 45-seconds. We don't want ERG mode grinding you to a halt because you cannot maintain the (ridiculously) high power targets. Even if you drop down below FTP in the final 10-seconds of these efforts, as long as you are going flat out, you are doing it correctly.

Just take this session one interval at a time, and focus on giving your all for this one effort. You can worry about the others when you get to them. If you finish this session without swearing, then you didn't go hard enough!

​

**Warm Up**

1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70

1 minute 15 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70

1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70

30 seconds @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <70

30 seconds @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70

30 seconds @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <70

45 seconds @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <90

30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70

15 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105

45 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70

15 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 200% of FTP -- HR >105

1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70

​

**Main Effort**

Number of Sets: 6

Rest Between Sets: 5 minutes 15 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70

Interval Repeats Per Set: N/A

**Interval**

Effort: 45 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105

​

**Extra Volume**

N/A

​

**Cool Down**

4 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70

prospects.name: Blender (Mini Version)
prospects.description: _Mini Blender_ takes all the best parts of the SUF classic _Blender_ and condenses them into a workout that's less than 60-minutes long. The sustained efforts at the start ensure your Anaerobic Capacity (AC) and Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) are really put to the test during the two sets of micro-intervals (the dreaded "Pain Shakes"). Just like the regular _Blender_, throwing some shorter threshold efforts your way after those AC and MAP builders means that your FTP doesn’t get left out. A perfect session for those who want to hit lots of improvement areas within an hour.

prospects.name: Serbia Upside Down Ep. 4
prospects.description:
🎬 Film: Serbia. A small country in the Balkan Peninsula that hides some of the most beautiful natural wonders and unique cultural heritage in this part of the world. Yet it remains unknown to many. Only the alternative, curious and brave plan their journeys in this hidden gem. However, a small self-organized crew from Serbia and Germany set a mission to discover and reveal those stunning natural creations of Serbia. On a bicycle. In just five days, they traversed 450 kilometers across six mountains of Western Serbia, and climbed around 11,000 meters to film and produce what you are about to experience.

​

🚴 Workout: This is a great way to watch a compelling documentary while developing your baseline aerobic fitness. The intensity of this workout will vary mostly between 60-70% of FTP, with heart rate remaining entirely in zone 2. This session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing.

prospects.name: Angels
prospects.description: If you were eating lunch, eight minutes wouldn't seem like a lot of time. If you were on a beach, it would be cruel to only be there for eight minutes. But during the eight-minute efforts in _Angels_, you'll think that it's never going to end. The focus on lower cadences and power targets near or above FTP makes this session perfect for improving your ability to crush shorter climbs. The longer efforts are designed to target your sustained aerobic system, which is great for improving FTP. They're also just short— and difficult—enough that you can drive improvements in Maximal Aerobic Power.

prospects.name: FTP Over-Unders: 3 Sets 8 x 1
prospects.description:
Over-Unders are one of those tried and true sessions that folks have been using for years to improve their FTP and get faster.

​

This session works on the same physiological principal as sessions like Who Dares and Fight Club. Those sessions hit you with short efforts well above FTP, followed by longer efforts moderately below FTP.
The concept is simple: you alternate blocks of time just below your FTP, with equal duration blocks just above your FTP. For this session, each interval is 8-minutes in length, with 1-minute blocks at 95% of FTP (Under) and 1-minute blocks at 105% of FTP (Over).


The real training benefit comes from that time spent just below FTP trying to "Recover." Physiologically, you train your body to be more efficient when working just below FTP. Mentally, it shows you that you can still "recover" (or at least hold on for dear life) as long as you are riding just a little below your FTP.

​

**Warm Up **

1 minutes 15 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%

1 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%

prospects.name: 2 x 2K Increasing
prospects.description:
If you drill into the pacing strategies of any endurance competitor, you quickly learn that the negative split is the fastest way to complete a course. A negative split is where your pace is higher during the second half of the course; we’ll work on that pacing strategy today.

​

For help understanding your run workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ).

Learn how to perform your [**Running Drills**](https://support.wahoofitness.com/hc/en-us/articles/4404080091922-Running-Drills) here.

​

**Warm-Up**

10 minutes @ RPE 2-4 -- 120-145% of RTP -- HR 70-87% (Z2)

​

**Activation 1: Drills of choice: butt kicks, high knees, etc.**

Number of Sets: 2

Rest Between Sets: 30 sec

Interval Distance: 25m

**Activation 2: 150-200m Strides**

Number of Sets: 2-3

Rest Between Sets: 30 sec

Interval Effort: 110-100% RTP (Z4a)

​

**Main Effort**

Number of Sets: 2

Rest Between Sets: 5 minutes

Interval Distance Per set: 2K

Interval Effort: Begin @ RPE 5-6 --120-110% of RTP --HR 87-95% (Z3)

Steadily increase to RPE 7.5-8.5 by final 400m -- 100-92% of RTP--HR 100-105% (Z4b)

Note: Repeat the same pace on the second set, but strive to finish faster for the final 400m.

​

**Cool Down**

5-10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 145% of RTP -- HR <70% (Z1)

prospects.name: 3 x 15 minute tempo
prospects.description:

Learn how to perform your [**Running Drills**](https://support.wahoofitness.com/hc/en-us/articles/4404080091922-Running-Drills) here.

​

Remember that tempo pace is not fast! The goal of this run is to find a steady rhythm/pace that you could comfortably hold for an hour or more.

​

**Warm-Up**

​

**Activation 1: Drills**

Number of Sets: 2

Rest Between Sets: 30 sec

Interval Distance: 25m each: butt kicks, high knees, Carioca, skipping

​

**Main Effort:**

Number of Sets 3

Rest Between Sets 5 minutes

Interval Repeats Per set 15 minutes

Interval Effort: RPE 5-6 --120-110% of RTP --HR 87-95% (Z3) Recovery: RPE <2 -->145% of RTP --HR<70% (Z1)

​

**Cool-down:**

End your workout with 5-10 minutes of easy jogging (Z1)

​

If you drill into the pacing strategies of any endurance competitor, you quickly learn that the negative split is the fastest way to complete a course. A negative split is where your pace is higher during the second half of the course. The goal of this workout is to practice that pacing strategy today.

​

**Warm-up**

10 minutes @ RPE 2-4 -- 120-145% of RTP -- HR 70-87% (Z2)
